<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.abc.net.au/news/politics/2002/11/item20021110144902_1.htm">Source.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
The Defence Minister Robert Hill has rejected suggestions Australia is ignoring a nuclear threat in North Korea. <br>
<br>
The Federal Opposition says Pyongyang poses a much more serious threat than Iraq because it is stockpiling enriched uranium.<br>
<br>
The Australian Government believes North Korea may already have a small number of nuclear weapons.<br>
<br>
But Senator Hill has told Channel Ten it is only been revealed in the past few weeks. <br>
<br>
&quot;And the response at the moment is to gather powerful regional states that all have a common interest that this weapons program not be pursued in North Korea... that's Russia China the United States and Japan, and to engage them in a process to seek to influence or gain influence North Korea to abandon that path,&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
***********************************************************************************<br>
<br>
Ha! Not unless they get offered something. Why would America, China or India give up it's nuclear arsenals? They wouldn't. Time to admit that they are part of the growing nuclear club and there's not a hell of a lot anybody can do about it. Should have considered this imminent event 20 years ago. While we bow down to protestors and let our aging nuclear weapons fade away, NK will be selling shiny new ones to whomever can afford the trade. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 67<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 8:42:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=165.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Oz Nukes</span><hr size=1> As an interested foreigner, I want to make a modest suggestion that would, nevertheless, probably get me lynched by the Oz watermelon faction: Independence minded Australians should at least consider the possibility of developing an independent nuclear deterrent. This has been within Australia's capability for decades and it is my understanding that it was seriously considered in the early 50s.<br>
<br>
Under the current arrangement, Australia must rely completely* on the United States to deter any nuclear threat from China or a rogue state. These threats can only become more numerous in the future, and may already be more numerous than is commonly realized. During the Cold War, when the Soviet Union was the threat, reliance on the US made sense. In the murky world of today, and the murkier world of the future, it may be much less certain. <br>
<br>
It is not impossible, perish the thought, that some unfortunate sequence of events could bring an isolationist, pacifist, and anti-nuclear administration to power in the US. There are certainly enough misguided watermelons and fellow-travellers working toward that goal, and they have recently been joined by far-right religious elements. The same might happen in Australia, but such a political catastrophe in Australia would not leave that country, let alone the US, naked against nuclear aggression. If it happened in the US, you would be defenseless through events over which you have no control. Is this acceptable to a sovereign state?<br>
 You can still count on us for now, but are you really willing to bet your national independence on this arrangement continuing forever? <br>
<br>
*there is a very slight, actually just hypothetical, possibility of the small and rigidly deployed British nuclear force coming into play, but it would be unwise to count on such a thing.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 371<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 3:46:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=165.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://image1ex.villagephotos.com/extern/935754.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Oz Nukes</span><hr size=1> I think there's more than a good chance that Australia could become a target of terrorist activities considering that it's surrounded by a number of unstable countries that hate the USA and anybody that's allied with it.  They've already been the victim of one big terrorist act.    <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/10/02 4:30:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=165.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Oz Nukes</span><hr size=1> Australia would be perfect for developing a small deterant force. Lacking the massive manpower of its potentialy threatening neighbors, a nuclear deterant would be an efficient method of defense. The Kiwis would whine about it though. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 2406<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/12/02 1:49:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=165.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Oz Nukes</span><hr size=1> We probably already have nuclear missiles. There are enough American bases over here and nobody knows what happens inside them. We are in a strategically important location. One that is within closer striking distance of both Russia and China. I wouldn't be surprised if the US has taken advantage of the situation. <br>
